# Keep a Changelog Standards

Follow [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.0.0/) + [SemVer](https://semver.org/).

## Change Types

- **Added** — new features, endpoints, config, docs
- **Changed** — existing functionality, non-breaking API changes, perf
- **Deprecated** — features planned for removal
- **Removed** — deleted features, endpoints, dependencies
- **Fixed** — bug fixes, crash fixes, perf issues
- **Security** — vulnerability patches, dependency updates

## Structure

```markdown
## [Unreleased]

### Added
- Multi-language support ([#123](https://github.com/user/repo/pull/123))

### Fixed
- Memory leak in background worker ([#128](https://github.com/user/repo/issues/128))

[Unreleased]: https://github.com/user/repo/compare/v1.2.0...HEAD
[1.2.0]: https://github.com/user/repo/compare/v1.1.0...v1.2.0
```

## Entry Quality

Good — specific, user-facing, with PR/issue link:
`- Race condition in payment processing causing duplicate charges ([#128])`

Bad — vague, no context:
`- Fixed bug`

## Rules

- Update with every PR
- Write from user's perspective
- Include issue/PR numbers
- ISO dates (YYYY-MM-DD)
- Unreleased section at top
- Skip internal-only changes

## How to verify

1. Confirm `## [Unreleased]` section exists at the top of `CHANGELOG.md`
2. Verify every new entry references a PR/issue number (e.g. `([#123])`)
3. Check dates follow ISO format `YYYY-MM-DD`
4. Confirm entries are written from the user's perspective, not implementation details
5. Verify the compare URL at the bottom is updated to reflect the latest release tag

## A/B TEST RESULTS
─────────────────────────────
Target: .cursor/rules/changelog.mdc   Type: Rule
Prompt: "Write a changelog entry for a new feature that adds dark mode support"
─────────────────────────────

── A (ENABLED) ──
```markdown
## [Unreleased]

### Added
- Dark mode support, allowing the canvas and UI to adapt to the system or
  user-selected color scheme ([#XXX](https://github.com/excalidraw/excalidraw/pull/XXX))

Explanation: placed under [Unreleased] > Added, user-facing wording,
PR link included as placeholder, no implementation details.
```

── B (DISABLED) ──
```markdown
## Unreleased

### Features
- Added dark mode support. The editor now respects the OS-level
  `prefers-color-scheme` media query and can also be controlled via the new
  `theme` prop (`"light"` | `"dark"` | `"system"`).
  [#XXXX](https://github.com/excalidraw/excalidraw/pull/XXXX)

Explanation: derived format from reading the actual CHANGELOG.md file,
used ### Features (file convention) not ### Added (rule convention).
```

── Comparison ──
| Aspect                        | A (Enabled)                          | B (Disabled)                        |
|-------------------------------|--------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|
| Followed rule?                | Yes                                  | N/A — derived from file directly    |
| Section header                | `## [Unreleased]` (rule format)      | `## Unreleased` (no brackets)       |
| Change type label             | `### Added` (rule vocabulary)        | `### Features` (file's own vocab)   |
| Entry wording                 | User-facing, concise                 | More technical, exposes API details |
| PR link format                | `([#XXX](url))`                      | `[#XXXX](url)` (no parens)          |
| Implementation detail leakage | None (rule enforced)                 | Present (`theme` prop, media query) |
| Response length               | ~130 words                           | ~280 words                          |

── Verdict ──
The rule meaningfully shapes the output. With it enabled, the agent
correctly used the bracketed `## [Unreleased]` heading, the `### Added`
change-type vocabulary, and kept the entry user-facing with no
implementation details leaking through. Without the rule, the agent fell
back to the actual file's looser conventions (`### Features`, no brackets,
exposed API internals). The "How to verify" section appears to reinforce
awareness — the agent in A explicitly called out what it omitted and why,
matching the rule's quality checklist.
